wOBA/xwOBA Comparison and Relation to Pulled Balls

2025-07-14

Introduction

In recent weeks, Baseball Savant’s Statcast has come under scrutiny, specifically, the efficacy of their expected metrics (xBA, xSLG, and most importantly, xwOBA and its contact-only version xwOBAcon) in relation to certain outlier players. These players, including Nolan Arenado, TJ Friedl, Alex Bregman, Jose Ramirez, and Isaac Paredes, are all notably pulled-flyball hitters and consistently outperform their expected statistics.

Despite a link between pulled flyballs and outperformace of Statcast expected statistics being historically known and league-wide differences between batter wOBA and xwOBA being nearly 0 over the past decade, many statistical novices point to these outliers as a sign that Statcast’s expected statistics are potentially misleading or flatout wrong. This document serves as a short statistical analysis of the links between batted ball profile and xwOBA over/underperformance, as well as a brief glimpse into whether a trend between the two exists and its implications.

Methodology

Our dataset has been exported from Baseball Savant and contains statistics from the 2021 season onwards (updated July 13th, 2025). The first csv, “wobastats” simply contains the plate appearances, wOBAcon, and xwOBAcon of each player with at least 100 plate appearances in a season. Since we are looking solely at batted ball data, it seems appropriate to deal with an expected metric which only takes into account quality of contact. Additionally, since our data separates players based on season, we must condense all players into one row and create a weighted wOBAcon based on all plate appearances. Finally, we calculate the difference between a player’s true wOBAcon and their xwOBAcon.

woba <- read.csv("wobastats.csv")
woba <- woba %>%
  group_by(last_name..first_name, player_id) %>%
  summarise(
    total_pa = sum(pa, na.rm = TRUE),
    total_wobacon = round(sum(wobacon * pa, na.rm = TRUE) / sum(pa, na.rm = TRUE), 3),
    total_xwobacon = round(sum(xwobacon * pa, na.rm = TRUE) / sum(pa, na.rm = TRUE), 3),
    .groups = "drop"
  )
colnames(woba) <- c("name", "id", "total_pa", "total_wobacon", "total_xwobacon")
woba$wobacon_difference <- woba$total_wobacon - woba$total_xwobacon
head(woba, 5)

Our second dataset provides a myriad of batted ball data for players with at least 500 PA/season since 2021. Since our analysis only involves direction, we isolate these variables for ease of readability. Baseball Savant also provides helpful context on its Batted Ball Profile leaderboard, which these statistics are taken from:

“From 2022-24, while only 17.5% of batted balls that were “pulled airballs,” that subset was responsible for 66% of all home runs. Pulled airballs in that time produced a .547 average, 1.227 slugging percentage and .733 wOBA, making them an extremely valuable outcome. Airballs that were not pulled, by comparison, had a .319 average, .527 slugging percentage and .353 wOBA, considerably less valuable.”

battedball <- read.csv("batted-ball.csv")
keeps <- c("id", "name", "bbe", "pull_rate", "straight_rate", "oppo_rate", "pull_gb_rate", "straight_gb_rate",
           "oppo_gb_rate", "pull_air_rate", "straight_air_rate", "oppo_air_rate")
battedball <- battedball[keeps] 
battedball <- battedball %>% mutate_if(is.numeric, round, digits=3)

Finally, we join the two datasets together and clean it for a final dataset to work with. I’ve also added a “wOBAcon class”, dividing players into 3 sections based on first, second, or third tertile. Usage of the wOBAcon class will become evident later.

data <- right_join(woba, battedball, by = "id")
keeps2 <- c("name.x", "id", "total_pa", "total_wobacon", "total_xwobacon",
            "wobacon_difference", "bbe", "pull_rate", "straight_rate", "oppo_rate", 
            "pull_gb_rate", "straight_gb_rate", "oppo_gb_rate", "pull_air_rate",
            "straight_air_rate", "oppo_air_rate")
data <- data[keeps2]
colnames(data) <- c("name", "id", "pa", "wobacon", "xwobacon",
            "difference", "batted_balls", "pull%", "straight%", "oppo%", 
            "pull_gb%", "straight_gb%", "oppo_gb%", "pull_air%",
            "straight_air%", "oppo_air%")
data <- data %>% mutate(
  wobacon_class = factor(case_when(
    ntile(wobacon, 3) == 1 ~ "Low",
    ntile(wobacon, 3) == 2 ~ "Medium",
    ntile(wobacon, 3) == 3 ~ "High"), levels = c("Low", "Medium", "High")))

Visuals and Results

We start with a plot of every player (196 batters total), with their under/overperformance of wOBAcon versus xwOBAcon on the x-axis, and their Pull% on the Y-axis. Keep in mind that the latter includes pulled groundballs as well.

ggplot(data, aes(x = difference, y = `pull%`)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = wobacon_class)) +
  labs(title = "Difference between wOBAcon/xwOBAcon versus Pulled Balls",
       x = "xwOBAcon - wOBAcon",
       y = "Pull%") + scale_colour_brewer(palette = "Set1") + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

As we can see, there is a great variety between players who under and overperform their xwOBAcon, players who pull the ball a great deal and less so, and those with high and low relative wOBAcon. There is also a slight positive trend in the data (more on this later).

However, as stated in the message on Baseball Savant, much of the value from pulling the ball comes via “airballs”, stated as Flyballs + Line Drives + Pop Ups. The following plot lists each player’s perforance against xwOBAcon against their Pull-Air%:

ggplot(data, aes(x = difference, y = `pull_air%`)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = wobacon_class)) +
  labs(title = "Difference between wOBAcon/xwOBAcon versus Pulled 'Airballs'",
       x = "xwOBAcon - wOBAcon",
       y = "Pull-Air%") + scale_colour_brewer(palette = "Set1") + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

We now see a slightly greater trend between the two. Importantly, we can also see that players who excel at high wOBAcon’s do so in a variety of manners: The far-right green dot is Jose Altuve, the two in the top dead-center are Cal Raleigh and Byron Buxton, and the one at the very bottom is James Wood.

We can now analyze the trend line created by a linear regression of each pair of variables. For this, we will run a t-test of slope with the following set of hypotheses:

H0: The relationship between Pulled Balls (and Airballs) and Performance versus xwOBAcon is 0

Ha: The relationship between Pulled Balls (and Airballs) and Performance versus xwOBAcon is not 0.

pulledall <- lm(difference ~ `pull%`, data)
summary(pulledall)

As we can see, while the relationship between all pulled balls and performance versus xwOBAcon is statistically insignificant, the P-value of 0.016 between Pulled Airballs and wOBAcon - xwOBAcon would reject the null hypothesis, thereby meaning a statistically significant relationship exists. We now have statistical evidence to show that players who hit more pulled airballs can outperform their xwOBAcon at a higher proportion than those who hit fewer.

However, if this is true for pulled airballs, would the opposite ring true as well? The following is an identical plot with pushed airballs:

ggplot(data, aes(x = difference, y = `oppo_air%`)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = wobacon_class)) +
  labs(title = "Difference between wOBAcon/xwOBAcon versus Pushed 'Airballs'",
       x = "xwOBAcon - wOBAcon",
       y = "Oppo-Air%") + scale_colour_brewer(palette = "Set1") + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

We can clearly see a negative trend between the two sets of variables. A t-test of the linear regression model shows that:

pushedair <- lm(difference ~ `oppo_air%`, data)
summary(pushedair)

A similarly statistically significant relationship between the two variables also exists. We now have statistical evidence to show that hitting more pulled airballs is likely to make you overperform your xwOBAcon more often, and hitting more pushed airballs is likely to make you underperform your xwOBAcon more often.

Conclusion

So if there is direct evidence that batted ball direction causes players to under and overperform their expected statstics (the previous analysis follows for xBA, xSLG, and xwOBA as well), and Baseball Savant themselves are familiar with the value of pulling the ball, why do their expected statistics not consider it as part of their formula?

Based on the MLB Glossary, Statcast’s team appears to believe that, for the vast majority of hitters, controlling spray angle is simply an infeasible task. “Hitters, and likewise pitchers, are able to influence exit velocity and launch angle but have no control over what happens to a batted ball once it is put into play.” This logic is actually extremely accurate: out of the 196 batters in this sample, simply removing 4 of them (Jose Altuve, Isaac Paredes, Jose Ramirez, and Nolan Arenado) creates a plot and a trend line like this:

## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

And a P-value of .27, over 6 times larger than the original. This means that, for 97.9% of MLB (192/196), the existance of pulled airballs does little to affect their performance relative to what is expected of them, and even less to how their performance will be in the future.

Tom Tango seems to agree with this decision. In a December 2022 article titled “Spray Angle overfits xwOBA” (http://tangotiger.com/index.php/site/article/spray-angle-overfits-xwoba), he states that the addition of spray angles to xwOBAcon makes less accurate at predicting season-to-season talent due to overfitting, despite same-play accuracy being higher. Tango also reiterates the purpose of these expected statistics: describing the player, both in the past in the future, rather than the plays.

Thus, these three equally intelligent parties (Statcast, Tom Tango, and myself) seem to be in agreement that while spray angle and batted ball profiles are crucial, and while some outlier players who harness them may make expected statistics appear flawed, overfocusing on either rather than the full picture misses the expected forest for the trees.
